==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /si:θ/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[sith-]]'', whence also Old High German ''[[sīd]]'', Old Norse ''[[síðr]]''
====Adjective/Adverb====
'''sīþ'''

# [[late]]

====Reposition/Conjunction====
'''sīþ'''

# [[after]]

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sinþ''.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''sīþ'', Old High German ''[[sind]]'', ''sint'', Old Norse ''sinn'' (Icelandic ''[[sinni]]''), Gothic [[𐍃𐌹𐌽𐌸𐍃]].  The root is a variant of the ancestor of ''[[sendan]]''.
====Noun====
'''sīþ''' ''m'' (pl. ''sīþas'')

# a [[journey]], a [[movement]]
#:''Brim berstende blodegesan hweop sæmanna sið'': the bursting ocean had threatened the seamen’s journey with blood-fear.  (''Junius Exodus'')
# a [[time]] or [[occasion]]
#:''ða wæs forma sið deorum madme þæt his dom alæg'': that was the first time for the precious treasure that its renown failed.  (''Beowulf 1527'')

====Noun====
'''sīþ''' ''m'' (used in the form ''ġesīþ'')

# fellow [[passenger]]

